ith user confirmation.\\n\\nThis is a safe design: reads never mutate, writes only reconcile at push time (when the user is already syncing), and manual repair is available via `entire doctor`. The cherry-pick approach preserves all data since checkpoint shards use unique paths.\\n\\nTest coverage is good: 6 reconciliation tests covering no-remote, no-local, same-hash, shared ancestry, disconnected, multi-commit, and modified entries scenarios. The gitops/diff.go tests are thorough.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Critical Issues (90-100)\\n\\nNo critical issues found.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Important Issues (80-89)\\n\\n**Issue 1: `WarnIfMetadataDisconnected` swallows errors silently and uses `os.Stderr` instead of the logging package**\\nConfidence: 85\\n\\nFile: `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/metadata_reconcile.go`, lines 62-76\\n\\nThe `WarnIfMetadataDisconnected` function writes directly to `os.Stderr` using `fmt.Fprintln`, but per CLAUDE.md's \\\"Logging vs User Output\\\" section, operational messages (which this is -- a diagnostic about metadata branch state) should use the `logging` package, not `fmt.Print*`. Additionally, the function swallows all errors silently (line 71: `if err != nil || !disconnected { return }`), which makes debugging difficult when the check itself fails.\\n\\n```go\\nfunc WarnIfMetadataDisconnected() {\\n\\tdisconnectedOnce.Do(func() {\\n\\t\\tctx := context.Background()\\n\\t\\trepo, err := OpenRepository(ctx)\\n\\t\\tif err != nil {\\n\\t\\t\\treturn  // error swallowed\\n\\t\\t}\\n\\t\\tdisconnected, err := IsMetadataDisconnected(ctx, repo)\\n\\t\\tif err != nil || !disconnected {\\n\\t\\t\\treturn  // error swallowed\\n\\t\\t}\\n\\t\\tfmt.Fprintln(os.Stderr, \\\"[entire] Warning: ...\\\")  // should use logging or cmd.ErrOrStderr\\n\\t})\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThis is a user-facing warning, so `fmt.Fprintln(os.Stderr, ...)` is arguably acceptable for the warning itself (the user needs to see it). However, the error on line 71 should at least be logged via `logging.Debug` so failures are diagnosable. Consider:\\n\\n```go\\nif err != nil {\\n    logging.Debug(ctx, \\\"metadata disconnection check failed\\\", slog.String(\\\"error\\\", err.Error()))\\n    return\\n}\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n**Issue 2: `ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch` writes user-facing progress to `os.Stderr` instead of accepting an `io.Writer`**\\nConfidence: 82\\n\\nFile: `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/metadata_reconcile.go`, lines 132, 158, 162, 175\\n\\nThe function writes progress messages directly to `os.Stderr`:\\n```go\\nfmt.Fprintln(os.Stderr, \\\"[entire] Detected disconnected session metadata ...\\\")\\nfmt.Fprintln(os.Stderr, \\\"[entire] Done — local had no checkpoint data, reset to remote\\\")\\nfmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \\\"[entire] Cherry-picking %d local checkpoint(s) onto remote...\\\\n\\\", len(dataCommits))\\nfmt.Fprintln(os.Stderr, \\\"[entire] Done — all local and remote checkpoints preserved\\\")\\n```\\n\\nThis is called from two places: `push_common.go` (hook context, where `os.Stderr` is fine) and `doctor.go` (command context, where `cmd.ErrOrStderr()` should be used for testability). While the current callers happen to work with `os.Stderr`, this makes the function harder to test and goes against the CLAUDE.md pattern of using `cmd.ErrOrStderr()` for user-facing output in commands.\\n\\nSuggestion: Accept an optional `io.Writer` parameter or move the user messages to the callers, letting the core function return structured results.\\n\\n---\\n\\n**Issue 3: `filesChangedInCommit` returns empty map on error instead of propagating it**\\nConfidence: 83\\n\\nFile: `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_hooks.go`, lines 2132-2148 (in the new version)\\n\\n```go\\nfunc filesChangedInCommit(ctx context.Context, repoDir string, commit *object.Commit) map[string]struct{} {\\n\\tvar parentHash string\\n\\tif commit.NumParents() > 0 {\\n\\t\\tparentHash = commit.ParentHashes[0].String()\\n\\t}\\n\\tresult, err := gitops.DiffTreeFiles(ctx, repoDir, parentHash, commit.Hash.String())\\n\\tif err != nil {\\n\\t\\tlogging.Warn(ctx, \\\"post-commit: git diff-tree failed; condensation and carry-forward may be affected\\\",\\n\\t\\t\\tslog.String(\\\"commit\\\", commit.Hash.String()),\\n\\t\\t\\tslog.String(\\\"error\\\", err.Error()),\\n\\t\\t)\\n\\t\\treturn make(map[string]struct{})\\n\\t}\\n\\treturn result\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThe old version had the same pattern (returning empty map on error), but the new version adds a warning log, which is an improvement. However, returning an empty `committedFileSet` silently breaks downstream condensation logic: the code at line 166 in `manual_commit_condensation.go` (`if len(committedFiles) > 0`) will skip the file filtering entirely, meaning all transcript-extracted files get included instead of just the ones in the commit. This is a silent data quality degradation rather than a clear error.\\n\\nThe CLAUDE.md says \\\"Handle all errors explicitly -- don't leave them unchecked.\\\" The old code already had this pattern, so this is pre-existing, but now that you are touching this function, consider having it return `(map[string]struct{}, error)` to let callers decide what to do.\\n\\n---\\n\\n**Issue 4: `collectCommitChain` follows only first parent, may miss commits on merge branches**\\nConfidence: 80\\n\\nFile: `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/metadata_reconcile.go`, lines 202-232\\n\\n```go\\nfunc collectCommitChain(repo *git.Repository, tip plumbing.Hash) ([]*object.Commit, error) {\\n\\t// ...\\n\\tif len(commit.ParentHashes) == 0 {\\n\\t\\treachedRoot = true\\n\\t\\tbreak\\n\\t}\\n\\tcurrent = commit.ParentHashes[0]  // Only first parent\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThe metadata branch (`entire/checkpoints/v1`) can have merge commits from `fetchAndMergeSessionsCommon`. If the local disconnected branch has merge commits (e.g., from a previous push-fetch-merge cycle), this function would only follow the first parent, potentially skipping the second parent's data when cherry-picking. However, for the specific \\\"empty-orphan bug\\\" this is fixing, the local branch is typically linear (it was created as an orphan with sequential checkpoint commits), so this is unlikely to be hit in practice. The comment on the function should note this limitation.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Summary\\n\\nThe PR is well-structured and solves a real problem (disconnected metadata branches from the empty-orphan bug) with a sound approach. The core reconciliation logic in `metadata_reconcile.go` is correct -- it properly detects disconnection via `git merge-base`, filters empty orphan commits, computes full deltas (adds + modifies + deletes), and cherry-picks them onto the remote tip. The `sync.Once` usage for warnings is appropriate.\\n\\nThe `gitops/diff.go` utility is a clean extraction that improves performance by using `git diff-tree` instead of go-git tree walks, with good test coverage including edge cases (renames, copies, deletions, subdirectories).\\n\\nThe main concerns are around the output pattern (direct `os.Stderr` writes from library-level functions, which affects testability) and the `filesChangedInCommit` error-swallowing pattern. These are not blocking but worth addressing for consistency with the project's established patterns.</result>\\n<usage><total_tokens>124569</total_tokens><tool_uses>37</tool_uses><duration_ms>140944</duration_ms></usage>\\n</task-notification>\\nFull transcript available at: /private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-alex-workspace-cli--worktrees-3/tasks/a1a00b4c55bcb8e50.output\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"dc285d5e-ef3a-4d82-a90d-00f9e1fafadd\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3\",\"sessionId\":\"042ac44f-5efd-4c35-8e56-7fedf6e12548\",\"version\":\"2.1.66\",\"gitBranch\":\"fix/reconcile-disconnected-metadata-branch\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\