oth unit tests (parser) and integration tests (real git repos). The `EnsureMetadataBranch` changes in `common.go` are properly tested with new cases validating that empty orphans get updated from remote and that disconnected branches are not auto-reconciled during enable.\\n\\nThe refactoring of `filesChangedInCommit` and `getAllChangedFilesBetweenTrees` (renamed to `getAllChangedFilesBetweenTreesSlow`) is handled cleanly with signature updates in tests and the deleted cache-equivalence test correctly reflects the removal of the old tree-caching approach.\\n\\n### 2. Critical Gaps\\n\\n**Gap 1: `collectCommitChain` depth limit exceeded -- Criticality 8/10**\\n\\nThe `collectCommitChain` function at `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/metadata_reconcile.go:203-232` has a safety limit of `MaxCommitTraversalDepth` (1000 commits). If the chain exceeds this, it returns an error:\\n\\n```go\\nif !reachedRoot {\\n    return nil, fmt.Errorf(\\\"commit chain exceeded %d commits without reaching root; aborting reconciliation\\\", MaxCommitTraversalDepth)\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThere is no test exercising this boundary. While constructing 1000+ commits in a test is impractical, a unit test with a smaller mock or a test that validates the error message format when the limit is reached would catch regressions if someone changes the depth constant or the loop logic. This is a safety mechanism protecting against infinite loops or corrupted repos, and verifying it works prevents silent corruption of the metadata branch.\\n\\n**What would break without this test**: If someone refactors the `for range MaxCommitTraversalDepth` to `for { }` or changes the break condition, an infinite loop would occur in production. A targeted unit test for `collectCommitChain` directly (perhaps with a circular commit reference mock, or a chain that is depth+1 long) would catch this.\\n\\n**Gap 2: `ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch` with only empty orphan commits -- Criticality 8/10**\\n\\nThe function at line 152-159 of `metadata_reconcile.go` handles the case where all local commits are empty-tree commits (the orphan bug commits) and no data commits exist:\\n\\n```go\\nif len(dataCommits) == 0 {\\n    // Local only had empty orphan - just point to remote\\n    ref := plumbing.NewHashReference(refName, remoteHash)\\n    if err := repo.Storer.SetReference(ref); err != nil {\\n        return fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to reset metadata branch to remote: %w\\\", err)\\n    }\\n    fmt.Fprintln(os.Stderr, \\\"[entire] Done - local had no checkpoint data, reset to remote\\\")\\n    return nil\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThe `TestReconcileDisconnected_MultipleLocalCheckpoints` test has an empty root commit among its chain, but data commits follow it. There is no dedicated test where *all* local commits are empty-tree orphans. This is the exact scenario the empty-orphan bug would create in a repo that was initialized with the bug but never had any local checkpoints condensed.\\n\\n**What would break without this test**: If someone accidentally removes the `len(dataCommits) == 0` early return, the code would attempt to cherry-pick zero commits onto the remote tip, which could behave unpredictably. A dedicated test would catch this.\\n\\n### 3. Important Improvements\\n\\n**Improvement 1: Deletion handling in `cherryPickOnto` -- Criticality 7/10**\\n\\nThe `cherryPickOnto` function at `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/metadata_reconcile.go:237-323` handles deletions (lines 276-281). The `TestReconcileDisconnected_ModifiedEntries` test covers modifications but not deletions. While checkpoint shards should only accumulate (add/modify), a test verifying that a commit that deletes a file from its parent correctly propagates that deletion during cherry-pick would strengthen confidence.\\n\\n**What it catches**: If the deletion logic at line 304 (`delete(mergedEntries, path)`) were removed or broken, stale files from earlier commits would persist in the final tree. A test with a local chain that deletes a file between commits would verify this.\\n\\n**Improvement 2: `checkDisconnectedMetadata` integration in `doctor.go` -- Criticality 6/10**\\n\\nThe `checkDisconnectedMetadata` function at `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/doctor.go:297-348` has no tests. It handles:\\n- The \\\"OK\\\" path when branches are not disconnected\\n- The interactive confirmation prompt path\\n- The `--force` flag path\\n- The error path when `IsMetadataDisconnected` fails\\n\\nWhile the underlying `IsMetadataDisconnected` and `ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch` are well-tested, the wiring in `doctor.go` that controls user interaction, error handling, and force-mode behavior has no direct test coverage. This is a Cobra command handler, which is harder to unit test, but the logic is non-trivial (prompt flow, error swallowing with warning, etc.).\\n\\n**What it catches**: If someone changes the `!force` check or removes the `formErr` error handling, users could lose data without confirmation. An integration-level test would verify the force path calls reconcile correctly.\\n\\n**Improvement 3: `WarnIfMetadataDisconnected` `sync.Once` behavior -- Criticality 5/10**\\n\\nThe `WarnIfMetadataDisconnected` function at `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/metadata_reconcile.go:62-76` uses a package-level `sync.Once` to ensure the warning fires at most once per process. This function is called from three different entry points (`common.go:126`, `manual_commit.go:54`, `explain.go:897`). There is no test verifying:\\n- The `sync.Once` ensures only one warning per process\\n- The graceful handling when `OpenRepository` fails\\n- The graceful handling when `IsMetadataDisconnected` returns an error\\n\\nThe `sync.Once` is a package-level global, which makes testing harder, but this function silently swallows errors, which is by design but worth verifying.\\n\\n**What it catches**: If someone replaces `sync.Once` with a simple function call, users would see the warning 3 times per session. If error handling changes and the function starts returning errors (breaking the silent contract), callers that don't handle errors would crash.\\n\\n**Improvement 4: `parseDiffTreeOutput` with `--root` format -- Criticality 5/10**\\n\\nThe `parseDiffTreeOutput` function at `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/gitops/diff.go:60-105` parses null-separated output from `git diff-tree`. The unit tests at lines 299-377 in `diff_test.go` test the standard format but not the `--root` format output, which has a slightly different structure (the status line format is identical, but the output includes an extra commit hash line at the beginning when using `--root` without `--no-commit-id`). The integration test `TestDiffTreeFiles_InitialCommit` does exercise the `--root` path through the actual git command, which provides good coverage. This is a minor gap.\\n\\n### 4. Test Quality Issues\\n\\n**Issue 1: Test helper `run()` duplication in `metadata_reconcile_test.go` -- Minor**\\n\\nThe `TestReconcileDisconnected_NoRemote` test at `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/metadata_reconcile_test.go:19-59` and `TestIsMetadataDisconnected_NoRemote` at lines 377-419 have nearly identical setup code (init repo, create orphan branch). The file already uses `initBareWithMetadataBranch` and `cloneWithConfig` helpers for the clone-based tests, but the local-only tests repeat setup inline. This is not a correctness issue but reduces maintainability.\\n\\n**Issue 2: Attribution tests pass empty strings for new parameters -- Minor**\\n\\nThe `manual_commit_attribution_test.go` changes consistently pass `\\\"\\\", \\\"\\\", \\\"\\\"` for the new `repoDir`, `attributionBaseCommit`, and `headCommitHash` parameters. This is correct behavior because it forces the slow tree-walk path (the tests were already testing this path). However, there is no test that exercises the *fast path* (passing real commit hashes through `getAllChangedFiles` to `DiffTreeFiles`). The fast path is implicitly tested through integration tests of the full condense flow, but a unit-level test would be valuable. This is low criticality since the `DiffTreeFiles` function itself is well-tested separately.\\n\\n### 5. Positive Observations\\n\\n**Well-structured scenario coverage for reconciliation**: The test file `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/metadata_reconcile_test.go` covers all the key early-exit paths methodically:\\n- No remote branch (line 19)\\n- No local branch (line 61)\\n- Same hash (line 79)\\n- Shared ancestry / diverged (line 101)\\n- Actual disconnected state (line 142)\\n- Multiple checkpoints (line 234)\\n- Modified entries between commits (line 544)\\n\\nThe tests for `IsMetadataDisconnected` mirror these same scenarios, providing independent coverage of the detection function separate from the repair function.\\n\\n**Good use of real git repos**: All tests use actual git repositories (via `t.TempDir()` and git CLI commands) rather than mocking git operations. This provides high confidence that the code works with real git semantics.\\n\\n**Thorough diff parser testing**: The `diff_test.go` file has excellent coverage of the `parseDiffTreeOutput` parser with edge cases including renames (R), copies (C), mixed operations, empty output, and the `extractStatus` function with all status types and malformed input.\\n\\n**Project conventions followed**: All tests use `t.Parallel()` correctly. Test helpers use `t.Helper()`. The test file organization follows the project pattern of one test file per production file.\\n\\n**Good assertions on cherry-pick results**: The `TestReconcileDisconnected_Disconnected` test (line 142) verifies multiple dimensions: linear history (not a merge), correct parentage, merged tree contains both local and remote data, and original commit message preservation. The `TestReconcileDisconnected_MultipleLocalCheckpoints` test further verifies commit ordering and that empty orphan commits are filtered out.\\n\\n**Correct removal of stale test**: The `TestFilesChangedInCommit_CacheEquivalence` test in `phase_postcommit_test.go` was properly removed since the caching approach was replaced with the `git diff-tree` CLI approach, and the test was testing implementation details that no longer exist.</result>\\n<usage><total_tokens>101562</total_tokens><tool_uses>30</tool_uses><duration_ms>150068</duration_ms></usage>\\n</task-notification>\\nFull transcript available at: /private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-alex-workspace-cli--worktrees-3/tasks/a1c7a099dc73e1332.output\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"7a14fd6a-7c93-4883-b577-162d36342d2c\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3\",\"sessionId\":\"042ac44f-5efd-4c35-8e56-7fedf6e12548\",\"version\":\"2.1.66\",\"gitBranch\":\"fix/reconcile-disconnected-metadata-branch\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_012oEPnyuKaBaPaSvf2QVV5o\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"<retrieval_status>timeout</retrieval_status>\"}]},\"uuid\":\"1bf84c34-a729-475a-bf1e-76ed7ea17eb3\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T23:37:46.863Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"retrieval_status\":\"timeout\",\"task\":null},\"sourceToolAssistantUUID\":\"7a14fd6a-7c93-4883-b577-162d36342d2c\"}\n{\"type\":\"queue-operation\",\"operation\":\"enqueue\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T23:38:34.283Z\",\"sessionId\":\"042ac44f-5efd-4c35-8e56-7fedf6e12548\",\"content\":\"<task-notification>\\n<task-id>a3c65728bdd489519</task-id>\\n<tool-use-id>REDACTED</tool-use-id>\\n<status>completed</status>\\n<summary>Agent \\\"Error handling review\\\" completed</summary>\\n<result>Now I have a thorough understanding of all the changed code. Let me compile my findings.\\n\\n---\\n\\n# Error Handling Audit: PR #533 -- Metadata Reconciliation\\n\\n## ISSUE 1: `WarnIfMetadataDisconnected` silently swallows ALL errors\\n\\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/metadata_reconcile.go`, lines 62-76\\n\\n**Severity:** HIGH\\n\\n**Issue Description:**\\nThe `WarnIfMetadataDisconnected` function silently returns on any error from `OpenRepository` or `IsMetadataDisconnected`. The combined condition `if err != nil || !disconnected` on line 70 merges two very different cases: \\\"we checked and it's not disconnected\\\" (benign) and \\\"we failed to check\\\" (potentially masking a real problem). There is no logging for the error case.\\n\\n**Hidden Errors:**\\n- Repository corruption that prevents opening (`OpenRepository` failure)\\n- Permission errors reading git refs\\n- `git merge-base` binary not found or failing\\n- Disk I/O errors during reference resolution\\n- Context cancellation during the check\\n\\n**User Impact:**\\nIf something is genuinely broken with the repository (e.g., corrupt refs, permission issues), the user gets zero indication. The `sync.Once` means this error path can only fire once per process -- after that, even if the underlying problem is transient, the warning will never be shown.\\n\\n**Recommendation:**\\nLog the error at debug level so there is some trace when things go wrong. The `sync.Once` semantics make this particularly important because the first failure permanently suppresses all future attempts.\\n\\n```go\\nfunc WarnIfMetadataDisconnected() {\\n\\tdisconnectedOnce.Do(func() {\\n\\t\\tctx := context.Background()\\n\\t\\trepo, err := OpenRepository(ctx)\\n\\t\\tif err != nil {\\n\\t\\t\\tlogging.Debug(ctx, \\\"metadata disconnection check: could not open repository\\\",\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tslog.String(\\\"error\\\", err.Error()))\\n\\t\\t\\treturn\\n\\t\\t}\\n\\t\\tdisconnected, err := IsMetadataDisconnected(ctx, repo)\\n\\t\\tif err != nil {\\n\\t\\t\\tlogging.Debug(ctx, \\\"metadata disconnection check failed\\\",\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tslog.String(\\\"error\\\", err.Error()))\\n\\t\\t\\treturn\\n\\t\\t}\\n\\t\\tif !disconnected {\\n\\t\\t\\treturn\\n\\t\\t}\\n\\t\\tfmt.Fprintln(os.Stderr, \\\"[entire] Warning: Local and remote session metadata branches are disconnected.\\\")\\n\\t\\tfmt.Fprintln(os.Stderr, \\\"[entire] Some checkpoints from remote may not be visible. Run 'entire doctor' to fix.\\\")\\n\\t})\\n}\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## ISSUE 2: `sync.Once` caches first-call result forever -- no retry on transient failures\\n\\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/metadata_reconcile.go`, lines 21, 62-76\\n\\n**Severity:** MEDIUM\\n\\n**Issue Description:**\\n`disconnectedOnce sync.Once` ensures the check runs at most once per process. This is fine for the \\\"disconnected\\\" or \\\"not disconnected\\\" outcomes, but if the first invocation fails due to a transient error (network timeout on git merge-base, brief I/O issue), `sync.Once` permanently marks the function as \\\"done.\\\" Every subsequent call to `WarnIfMetadataDisconnected` from `ListCheckpoints`, `getBranchCheckpoints`, or `getCheckpointStore` will silently skip the check.\\n\\n**User Impact:**\\nIf the first check happens during a transient failure (e.g., a momentary NFS glitch), the user will never see the disconnection warning for the entire process lifetime, even after the transient issue resolves.\\n\\n**Recommendation:**\\nThis is a design trade-off acknowledged by the `sync.Once` pattern. Consider documenting this explicitly in the function's godoc comment so future maintainers understand the trade-off. Alternatively, consider using a custom once-with-error pattern that retries on failure:\\n\\n```go\\n// Add a comment explaining the trade-off:\\n// WarnIfMetadataDisconnected checks (once per process) whether the metadata\\n// branch is disconnected and prints a warning to stderr if so.\\n// NOTE: Uses sync.Once, so transient failures on the first call permanently\\n// suppress the warning. This is acceptable because the check is advisory only\\n// and 'entire doctor' is the authoritative repair path.\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## ISSUE 3: `runSessionsFix` swallows `checkDisconnectedMetadata` error and continues\\n\\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/doctor.go`, lines 68-71\\n\\n**Severity:** HIGH\\n\\n**Issue Description:**\\nWhen `checkDisconnectedMetadata` returns an error, the doctor command prints a warning to stderr and continues to the stuck-sessions check. The function returns `nil` to the caller for this check, so the overall command reports success even when the metadata check failed. This is especially problematic because `entire doctor` is the recommended repair path -- if the repair itself fails, the user is told to run the very command that just silently failed.\\n\\n```go\\nif err := checkDisconnectedMetadata(cmd, force); err != nil {\\n    fmt.Fprintf(cmd.ErrOrStderr(), \\\"Warning: metadata check failed: %v\\\\n\\\", err)\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**Hidden Errors:**\\n- Repository open failures\\n- `IsMetadataDisconnected` errors (git merge-base failures, corrupt refs)\\n- `ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch` failures (cherry-pick failures, storage errors)\\n- All of these get reduced to a single-line warning that users will likely miss\\n\\n**User Impact:**\\nA user runs `entire doctor` as instructed by the warning message, sees \\\"Warning: metadata check failed: ...\\\" mixed in with other output, but the command exits 0. The user may think everything was fixed. The next `entire doctor` run will hit the same failure.\\n\\n**Recommendation:**\\nThe doctor command should accumulate errors and return a non-zero exit code if any check fails. At minimum, print a clearly visible error distinguishing \\\"check failed\\\" from \\\"nothing to fix\\\":\\n\\n```go\\nif err := checkDisconnectedMetadata(cmd, force); err != nil {\\n    fmt.Fprintf(cmd.ErrOrStderr(), \\\"Error: metadata check failed: %v\\\\n\\\", err)\\n    fmt.Fprintf(cmd.ErrOrStderr(), \\\"  Try running 'entire doctor' again. If the problem persists,\\\\n\\\")\\n    fmt.Fprintf(cmd.ErrOrStderr(), \\\"  please report this issue.\\\\n\\\")\\n    // Consider: return fmt.Errorf(\\\"metadata check failed: %w\\\", err)\\n    // or accumulate and return at the end\\n}\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## ISSUE 4: `fetchAndMergeSessionsCommon` swallows reconciliation failure\\n\\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/push_common.go`, lines 150-156\\n\\n**Severity:** HIGH\\n\\n**Issue Description:**\\nWhen `ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch` fails inside the push path, the error is printed as a warning and execution continues to the tree merge. This means the push path will proceed to merge trees of two disconnected branches -- the exact scenario reconciliation was supposed to fix. After reconciliation fails, the subsequent tree merge will silently combine the disconnected branch trees, potentially creating a merged result that obscures the disconnected state.\\n\\n```go\\nif reconcileErr := ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch(ctx, repo); reconcileErr != nil {\\n    fmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \\\"[entire] Warning: metadata reconciliation failed: %v\\\\n\\\", reconcileErr)\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**Hidden Errors:**\\n- Cherry-pick failures (storage errors, corrupt objects)\\n- Commit chain traversal exceeding depth limit\\n- Reference update failures\\n- All swallowed, then the code proceeds to do a tree merge that may produce bad results\\n\\n**User Impact:**\\nThe user's push appears to succeed (the pre-push hook does not fail), but the metadata branch may now contain a merge commit that combines two disconnected histories. This could create confusing checkpoint visibility issues that are harder to diagnose later than the original disconnected state.\\n\\n**Recommendation:**\\nIf reconciliation was attempted (because disconnection was detected) and failed, the tree merge should either (a) be skipped entirely, or (b) the error should be propagated to prevent a potentially incorrect merge:\\n\\n```go\\nif reconcileErr := ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch(ctx, repo); reconcileErr != nil {\\n    logging.Warn(ctx, \\\"metadata reconciliation failed; skipping tree merge to avoid corrupting branch\\\",\\n        slog.String(\\\"error\\\", reconcileErr.Error()))\\n    return fmt.Errorf(\\\"metadata reconciliation failed: %w\\\", reconcileErr)\\n}\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## ISSUE 5: `doPushBranch` first push failure is silently discarded\\n\\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/push_common.go`, lines 90-93\\n\\n**Severity:** MEDIUM\\n\\n**Issue Description:**\\nThe first `tryPushSessionsCommon` call's error is completely discarded -- not even logged. The code assumes any failure is \\\"likely non-fast-forward\\\" and proceeds to fetch-and-merge. But the error could be an auth failure, a network timeout, a corrupt ref, or any number of non-recoverable errors that fetch-and-merge will also fail on.\\n\\n```go\\n// Try pushing first\\nif err := tryPushSessionsCommon(ctx, remote, branchName); err == nil {\\n    return nil\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**Hidden Errors:**\\n- Authentication failures (SSH key issues, expired tokens)\\n- Network connectivity problems\\n- Remote repository not found\\n- Permission denied\\n- All of these trigger unnecessary fetch+merge attempts that will also fail\\n\\n**User Impact:**\\nWhen the real problem is authentication, the user sees two warning messages about \\\"couldn't sync\\\" and \\\"failed to push after sync\\\" but never sees the original error that explains the actual cause.\\n\\n**Recommendation:**\\nThis is a pre-existing pattern (not introduced by this PR), but the PR adds reconciliation into this error-swallowing chain. At minimum, log the first push error:\\n\\n```go\\nif err := tryPushSessionsCommon(ctx, remote, branchName); err == nil {\\n    return nil\\n}\\n// Log the initial push error for debugging\\nlogging.Debug(ctx, \\\"initial push failed, attempting fetch+merge recovery\\\",\\n    slog.String(\\\"branch\\\", branchName),\\n    slog.String(\\\"error\\\", err.Error()))\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## ISSUE 6: `pushBranchIfNeeded` silently returns nil on `OpenRepository` failure\\n\\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/push_common.go`, lines 38-41\\n\\n**Severity:** MEDIUM (pre-existing, but relevant to the push path changes)\\n\\n**Issue Description:**\\nThe `//nolint:nilerr // Hook must be silent on failure` comment explains the intent, but this means any repository corruption or access issue during pre-push is completely invisible. The nolint comment acknowledges this is intentional, but there is zero logging.\\n\\n```go\\nrepo, err := OpenRepository(ctx)\\nif err != nil {\\n    return nil //nolint:nilerr // Hook must be silent on failure\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**Hidden Errors:**\\n- Repository corruption\\n- Permission errors\\n- Working directory deleted\\n- git binary not found\\n\\n**User Impact:**\\nIf the repo cannot be opened during pre-push, the metadata push silently does not happen. The user has no way to know their checkpoints are not being pushed.\\n\\n**Recommendation:**\\nPre-existing pattern, but at minimum add debug logging:\\n\\n```go\\nrepo, err := OpenRepository(ctx)\\nif err != nil {\\n    logging.Debug(ctx, \\\"push: could not open repository, skipping metadata push\\\",\\n        slog.String(\\\"error\\\", err.Error()))\\n    return nil //nolint:nilerr // Hook must be silent on failure\\n}\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## ISSUE 7: `CalculateAttributionWithAccumulated` returns nil on `getAllChangedFiles` error\\n\\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_attribution.go`, lines 247-254\\n\\n**Severity:** MEDIUM\\n\\n**Issue Description:**\\nThis is a change in error behavior. Previously, the `getAllChangedFilesBetweenTrees` function was a pure in-memory operation unlikely to fail. Now `getAllChangedFiles` calls out to `git diff-tree` via `gitops.DiffTreeFileList`, which can fail due to external process errors (git binary issues, repo corruption, context cancellation). When it fails, the function logs a warning and returns `nil`, causing the entire attribution calculation to be skipped.\\n\\nThe logging addition is good -- this is actually an improvement over the pre-existing pattern where `getAllChangedFilesBetweenTrees` could also fail and would have returned an error that caused the same `return nil`. However, the severity of skipping attribution is now higher because the external dependency (git CLI) is more failure-prone than the previous in-memory approach.\\n\\n```go\\nallChangedFiles, err := getAllChangedFiles(ctx, baseTree, headTree, repoDir, attributionBaseCommit, headCommitHash)\\nif err != nil {\\n    logging.Warn(logging.WithComponent(ctx, \\\"attribution\\\"),\\n        \\\"attribution: failed to enumerate changed files\\\",\\n        slog.String(\\\"error\\\", err.Error()),\\n    )\\n    return nil\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**User Impact:**\\nWhen `git diff-tree` fails, the entire attribution data is silently dropped for that checkpoint. The checkpoint still gets condensed, but without attribution metadata. Users will not see attribution information for that checkpoint.\\n\\n**Recommendation:**\\nConsider falling back to the slow go-git tree walk when the fast path fails, rather than abandoning attribution entirely:\\n\\n```go\\nallChangedFiles, err := getAllChangedFiles(ctx, baseTree, headTree, repoDir, attributionBaseCommit, headCommitHash)\\nif err != nil {\\n    logging.Warn(logging.WithComponent(ctx, \\\"attribution\\\"),\\n        \\\"attribution: git diff-tree failed, falling back to tree walk\\\",\\n        slog.String(\\\"error\\\", err.Error()),\\n    )\\n    // Fall back to slow path\\n    allChangedFiles, err = getAllChangedFilesBetweenTreesSlow(ctx, baseTree, headTree)\\n    if err != nil {\\n        logging.Warn(logging.WithComponent(ctx, \\\"attribution\\\"),\\n            \\\"attribution: tree walk also failed, skipping attribution\\\",\\n            slog.String(\\\"error\\\", err.Error()),\\n        )\\n        return nil\\n    }\\n}\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## ISSUE 8: `filesChangedInCommit` returns empty map on `DiffTreeFiles` failure\\n\\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_hooks.go`, lines 2132-2145 (in the diff; actual line numbers in the new file)\\n\\n**Severity:** HIGH\\n\\n**Issue Description:**\\nThe refactored `filesChangedInCommit` switches from go-git tree diffs to `gitops.DiffTreeFiles`. When the external `git diff-tree` command fails, it logs a warning and returns an empty map. This empty map is then used by `PostCommit` to determine which files were committed. An empty `committedFileSet` has significant downstream consequences:\\n\\n1. **Condensation skip:** The `filesOverlapWithContent` check (used to decide whether to condense a session) will find no overlap between session files and committed files, potentially causing sessions to not be condensed when they should be.\\n2. **Carry-forward failure:** The committed file set is used to filter `filesTouched` during condensation. An empty set means all files get filtered out.\\n\\nThe pre-existing code (before this PR) also returned an empty map on failure from the go-git tree diff, so this is technically a pre-existing pattern. However, the new code has a higher failure probability since it shells out to an external process.\\n\\n```go\\nfunc filesChangedInCommit(ctx context.Context, repoDir string, commit *object.Commit) map[string]struct{} {\\n    ...\\n    result, err := gitops.DiffTreeFiles(ctx, repoDir, parentHash, commit.Hash.String())\\n    if err != nil {\\n        logging.Warn(ctx, \\\"post-commit: git diff-tree failed; condensation and carry-forward may be affected\\\",\\n            slog.String(\\\"commit\\\", commit.Hash.String()),\\n            slog.String(\\\"error\\\", err.Error()),\\n        )\\n        return make(map[string]struct{})\\n    }\\n    return result\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**User Impact:**\\nIf `git diff-tree` fails during PostCommit, sessions will not be properly condensed. The user's checkpoint data may be lost or incomplete. The warning message is good and mentions the downstream consequences, but it only appears in the debug log (`.entire/logs/`), not on stderr where users would see it.\\n\\n**Recommendation:**\\nThis is a significant failure mode. Consider falling back to the old go-git tree diff approach when the external command fails, rather than returning an empty set:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc filesChangedInCommit(ctx context.Context, repoDir string, commit *object.Commit, headTree, parentTree *object.Tree) map[string]struct{} {\\n    var parentHash string\\n    if commit.NumParents() > 0 {\\n        parentHash = commit.ParentHashes[0].String()\\n    }\\n    result, err := gitops.DiffTreeFiles(ctx, repoDir, parentHash, commit.Hash.String())\\n    if err != nil {\\n        logging.Warn(ctx, \\\"post-commit: git diff-tree failed, falling back to tree diff\\\",\\n            slog.String(\\\"commit\\\", commit.Hash.String()),\\n            slog.String(\\\"error\\\", err.Error()),\\n        )\\n        // Fall back to go-git tree diff\\n        return filesChangedInCommitFallback(commit, headTree, parentTree)\\n    }\\n    return result\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThis preserves the old behavior as a safety net while getting the performance benefit in the happy path.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## ISSUE 9: `getRepoPath` error lacks wrapping context\\n\\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/metadata_reconcile.go`, lines 357-363\\n\\n**Severity:** LOW\\n\\n**Issue Description:**\\n`getRepoPath` wraps its error, which is good. However, the callers of `getRepoPath` in `IsMetadataDisconnected` (line 52) do not add any additional context:\\n\\n```go\\nrepoPath, err := getRepoPath(repo)\\nif err != nil {\\n    return false, err  // No wrapping\\n}\\n```\\n\\nWhile `getRepoPath` itself wraps with \\\"failed to get worktree:\\\", the call site in `IsMetadataDisconnected` does not indicate which operation needed the repo path. This is a minor issue since the error chain is still informative.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## ISSUE 10: `explain.go` `ListCommitted` error silently sets `committedInfos = nil`\\n\\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3/cmd/entire/cli/explain.go`, lines 902-904\\n\\n**Severity:** MEDIUM (pre-existing, but the PR adds `WarnIfMetadataDisconnected` just above this)\\n\\n**Issue Description:**\\nThis is pre-existing code, but it interacts with the new warning. If the metadata branch is disconnected and `ListCommitted` fails as a result, the error is silently swallowed and `committedInfos` is set to nil. The new `WarnIfMetadataDisconnected()` call on line 897 is purely advisory and does not prevent this silent failure.\\n\\n```go\\ncommittedInfos, err := store.ListCommitted(ctx)\\nif err != nil {\\n    committedInfos = nil // Continue without committed checkpoints\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**User Impact:**\\nWhen the metadata branch is disconnected, committed checkpoints may fail to load, and the user sees no checkpoints without understanding why. The warning message (\\\"Run 'entire doctor' to fix\\\") appears on stderr but the empty checkpoint list appears on stdout with no explanation of the connection.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## POSITIVE OBSERVATIONS\\n\\nSeveral things are done well in this PR:\\n\\n1. **Error propagation in `ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch`:** The cherry-pick chain properly propagates errors up through `cherryPickOnto` -> `ReconcileDisconnectedMetadataBranch`. Every git operation in the chain has wrapped errors with context about what operation failed.\\n\\n2. **`isDisconnected` exit code handling:** The function properly distinguishes between exit code 1 (no common ancestor -- expected) and other exit codes (actual errors), avoiding the common mistake of treating all non-zero exits as \\\"disconnected.\\\"\\n\\n3. **`collectCommitChain` depth limit:** The `MaxCommitTraversalDepth` guard prevents unbounded traversal, with a clear error message when exceeded.\\n\\n4. **`checkDisconnectedMetadata` in doctor.go:** Properly handles `huh.ErrUserAborted` as a distinct case from other form errors.\\n\\n5. **`filesChangedInCommit` warning message:** The warning text \\\"condensation and carry-forward may be affected\\\" is specific about downstream consequences, which is better than a generic \\\"operation failed\\\" message.\\n\\n6. **`gitops/diff.go` error handling:** The `diffTreeRaw` function properly captures both stdout and stderr, and includes stderr content in the error message for debugging.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## SUMMARY\\n\\n| # | File | Severity | Issue |\\n|---|------|----------|-------|\\n| 1 | `metadata_reconcile.go:62-76` | HIGH | `WarnIfMetadataDisconnected` silently swallows all errors with no logging |\\n| 2 | `metadata_reconcile.go:21` | MEDIUM | `sync.Once` permanently suppresses check after transient failure |\\n| 3 | `doctor.go:68-71` | HIGH | Doctor command swallows metadata check failure, exits 0 |\\n| 4 | `push_common.go:154-156` | HIGH | Reconciliation failure swallowed, then proceeds to tree merge |\\n| 5 | `push_common.go:90-93` | MEDIUM | First push error completely discarded (pre-existing, but worsened) |\\n| 6 | `push_common.go:38-41` | MEDIUM | `OpenRepository` failure silent (pre-existing) |\\n| 7 | `manual_commit_attribution.go:247-254` | MEDIUM | Attribution skipped entirely on `git diff-tree` failure, no fallback |\\n| 8 | `manual_commit_hooks.go` (new `filesChangedInCommit`) | HIGH | Empty file set on diff-tree failure breaks condensation, no fallback |\\n| 9 | `metadata_reconcile.go:52` | LOW | Missing error context wrapping |\\n| 10 | `explain.go:902-904` | MEDIUM | Pre-existing silent failure now interacts with disconnection warning |\\n\\nThe most critical issues are **#3** (doctor command false success), **#4** (reconciliation failure followed by potentially-incorrect tree merge), and **#8** (empty committed file set breaking condensation). Issues #1 and #2 together mean the advisory warning system has a blind spot for transient failures.</result>\\n<usage><total_tokens>115745</total_tokens><tool_uses>22</tool_uses><duration_ms>203691</duration_ms></usage>\\n</task-notification>\\nFull transcript available at: /private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-alex-workspace-cli--worktrees-3/tasks/a3c65728bdd489519.output\"}\n{\"type\":\"queue-operation\",\"operation\":\"remove\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T23:38:34.305Z\",\"sessionId\":\"042ac44f-5efd-4c35-8e56-7fedf6e12548\"}\n{\"type\":\"queue-operation\",\"operation\":\"remove\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T23:38:34.305Z\",\"sessionId\":\"042ac44f-5efd-4c35-8e56-7fedf6e12548\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"b48da5b1-9559-48e1-99b2-8381785bbf16\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3\",\"sessionId\":\"042ac44f-5efd-4c35-8e56-7fedf6e12548\",\"version\":\"2.1.66\",\"gitBranch\":\"fix/reconcile-disconnected-metadata-branch\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01Xk6Uhi7aAb9VHr1GEkbJjW\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"<retrieval_status>timeout</retrieval_status>\"}]},\"uuid\":\"8dce9f69-45dd-4422-a374-fe2099530341\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T23:38:34.297Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"retrieval_status\":\"timeout\",\"task\":null},\"sourceToolAssistantUUID\":\"b48da5b1-9559-48e1-99b2-8381785bbf16\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"8dce9f69-45dd-4422-a374-fe2099530341\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/3\",\"sessionId\":\"042ac44f-5efd-4c35-8e56-7fedf6e12548\",\"version\":\"2.1.66\",\"gitBranch\":\"fix/reconcile-disconnected-metadata-branch\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_018DNwNvEkacegQnASqqBed8\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":